# ELBOT Deployment & Management Commands

---

## 1. Git Commands

### 1.1 Update Your Bot
```bash
git pull origin main
```
**Description**: Pulls the latest changes from the main branch of your repository.

### 1.2 Commit Changes
```bash
git add .
git commit -m "Your commit message here"
git push origin main
```
**Description**: Adds all changes, commits them with a message, and pushes them to the main branch.

### 1.3 Clone the Repository
```bash
git clone https://github.com/ALEPola/ELBOT.git
```
**Description**: Clones the ELBOT repo to your machine.

---

## 2. Bot Management Commands

### 2.1 Start the Bot
```bash
sudo systemctl start elbot.service
```
**Description**: Starts the bot as a systemd service.

### 2.2 Stop the Bot
```bash
sudo systemctl stop elbot.service
```
**Description**: Stops the bot service.

### 2.3 Restart the Bot
```bash
sudo systemctl restart elbot.service
```
**Description**: Restarts the bot to apply new changes or recover from errors.

### 2.4 Check Bot Status
```bash
sudo systemctl status elbot.service
```
**Description**: Shows the current status of the bot.

### 2.5 Enable Bot on Boot
```bash
sudo systemctl enable elbot.service
```
**Description**: Ensures the bot starts automatically when the system boots.

### 2.6 Disable Bot on Boot
```bash
sudo systemctl disable elbot.service
```
**Description**: Prevents the bot from starting automatically at boot.

---

## 3. System Monitoring Commands

### 3.1 View Logs for the Bot
```bash
sudo journalctl -u elbot.service --no-pager | tail -50
```
**Description**: Displays the latest 50 lines of logs for ELBOT.

#### 3.1.1 View Live Logs
```bash
sudo journalctl -u elbot.service -f
```
**Description**: Follows the log output live (like `tail -f`).

#### 3.1.2 View Today's Logs
```bash
sudo journalctl -u elbot.service --since today --no-pager
```
**Description**: Shows all logs from today.

> **Note:** If you see "No journal files were found", ensure `systemd-journald` is running and persistent logging is enabled on your system.

### 3.2 Monitor System Resources
```bash
top
```
**Description**: Real-time monitoring of CPU, memory, and processes.

---

## 4. File Management Commands

### 4.1 Edit Files with Nano
```bash
nano /path/to/file.py
```
**Description**: Opens a file for editing using the `nano` text editor.

### 4.2 Move Files
```bash
mv /path/to/source /path/to/destination
```
**Description**: Moves a file from one location to another.

### 4.3 Copy Files
```bash
cp /path/to/source /path/to/destination
```
**Description**: Copies a file from the source to the destination.

### 4.4 List Files in Directory
```bash
ls /path/to/directory
```
**Description**: Lists contents of a specified directory.

### 4.5 Change Directory
```bash
cd /path/to/directory
```
**Description**: Changes the current working directory.

---

## 5. Virtual Environment Management

### 5.1 Activate Virtual Environment
```bash
source /home/alex/ELBOT/venv/bin/activate
```
**Description**: Activates the virtual environment used by ELBOT.

### 5.2 Install Requirements
```bash
pip install -r requirements.txt
```
**Description**: Installs all Python dependencies needed to run ELBOT.

### 5.3 Deactivate Virtual Environment
```bash
deactivate
```
**Description**: Deactivates the currently active virtual environment.

---

## 6. Deployment Script

### 6.1 Run Deployment Script
```bash
./deploy.sh
```
**Description**: Executes the deployment script to update code and restart ELBOT.

### 6.2 Make Script Executable
```bash
chmod +x deploy.sh
```
**Description**: Allows the deploy script to be run as a command.

---

Make sure to check ELBOT logs after running deployments or restarting, using:
```bash
sudo journalctl -u elbot.service --no-pager | tail -50
```

This ensures the bot is running correctly.

ssh alex@192.168.1.5
cd ~/ELBOT 
python3 -m venv venv
source venv/bin/activate
chmod +x deploy.sh
./deploy.sh

chmod +x deploy_git_update.sh
./deploy_git_update.sh

# web
sudo systemctl daemon-reload
sudo systemctl restart elbot-web.service
chmod +x deploy_web.sh
sudo ./deploy_web.sh

